Independent schools in Scotland are constantly enjoying their scientific achievements — in 2018, they were able to boast of further excellent exam results, supported by individual and collective successes in sport, art, music, and more.
Represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) schools, attended by more than 30,000 students across Scotland, strive to provide the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further and higher education, the career path they have chosen, and to indicate their role as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector with the opportunity to develop and implement a curriculum tailored to the needs of the school, we see that modern languages are still popular and desirable subjects to choose from in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to another man in a language he understands, then it comes to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it comes to his heart.”
It is a clear reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The results of this year’s final exam show that languages rank first in the league rankings, with the highest performance rates in the case of independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who learned foreign languages received a higher A rating.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students had a higher A rating in Mandarin, and 72 percent of German learners, 69 percent of French learners and 63 percent of Spanish learners also had an A rating.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills, which children and young people will no doubt need in the future.
Currently, the study of languages, as subjects of choice, is conducted in the same scope as the study of STEM subjects (strict sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics) within the teaching programmes in independent schools and in other places.
A 2014 survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills (UK Commission for Employment and Skills) found that 17 percent of job vacancies were due to a lack of language skills for employers.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a necessity to prepare young people for the start of a professional career.
These skills are essential in a globalised world with an increasing number of jobs requiring language proficiency,
A lifelong skill, like learning a second language, will provide a huge advantage in the future – no matter what career path it takes.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically increases the chances of a multilingual person in relation to the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey, which involved more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75% of them were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only language with a percentage of 1 percent of the people using it.
That’s why investing in teaching foreign languages is so important for today’s children.
Knowledge of several languages, in particular the languages of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding the right job.
In Scotland, each school will be different in terms of the languages taught in it.
Many schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered to be the most important for the UK in the 2020 perspective, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the child’s interest, in independent schools there will always be many languages to choose from, which will be taught by specialized teaching staff in this area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a teaching environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed — no matter what the future holds for them.
At present, it cannot be denied that in the international business environment, languages are still crucial to the future of the country, so it must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be treated as “international communication skills” (international communication skills).
Independent schools will continue to offer Scottish youth a wide choice, diversity, and level.
You just have to.
