Harvard Students Attend a Course on Properly Long-Term Rest
The new course at Harvard University, which took place this year, provided all students with more sleep, aimed at combating the growing macho culture of learning by “all-night caffeine-driven students.”
Academic students from the best university in the world often have no idea about the basics of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course by giving a speech on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end of the speech, a girl approached me and said, ‘Why do I get told that only now that I’m in my last year of study?’
She said that no one ever told her about the meaning of sleep, which surprised me,” the Telegraph said.
During the course, which was held for the first time this year, students are explained how good sleep-related habits help achieve good results in science and sports, as well as improve the overall well-being of students.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health service, said the course was decided to be introduced after it was found that students suffered from a severe lack of sleep within a week.
The hourly course includes a number of interactive tasks.
One section includes a picture of the room in the academy, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise, and books to get information about the effects of caffeine and light, and how sleep deprivation affects sports performance, as well as how important it is to regulate sleep.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know that this will not lead to an immediate change in student behavior.
But we believe they have a right to know — just as everyone has a right to know what the health consequences of smoking cigarettes are,” added Professor Czeisler.
A culture of pride from “all-night science” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students means an increasing problem of sleep deprivation.
Providing enough good quality sleep should be the student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, and even to avoid gaining weight, because lack of sleep causes the brain to go into a state of starvation, starving the student.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemistry and physics, helped Professor Cheisler develop the course after taking part in one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push for the introduction of the course for the whole campus.
The next step, according to him, is to invite all postgraduate students to complete a similar degree program before moving on to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set an alarm reminding when to go to sleep and when to get up, as well as being aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by the screens of electronic devices and lighting problems with LEDs.
