Almanac: the inventor of the Geiger counter
And now the page from our edition “Sunday Morning” Almanac: September 30, 1882 — 136 years ago... the day on which the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm “Hans” Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, which eventually led to the creation of a device known as a Geiger counter.
Since then, Geiger's counter has become both an element of science and pop culture, as in the 1950 film Bells of Coronado, in which these seemingly unlikely cowboys-scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans performed:
Man: “What the hell is that?”
Rogers: “This is a Geiger counter that is used to locate radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
“When you put on these headphones, you’ll hear the effects of atoms emitted by radioactive minerals.”
Evans: “Now I hear something!”
Hans Geiger died in 1945, a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name has survived to this day.
A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to “watch” enemy cells.
New Cancer Vaccine Could Teach Your Immune System to “Watch” Enemy Cells and Destroy Them
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize enemy cells in the course of treatment.
This method consists of excreting immune cells from the patient and changing them into a laboratory.
Then they can "detect" the protein common to many cancers. Then they are injected back into the body.
The trial vaccine shows promising results in patients with different types of tumours.
In one woman who was given the vaccine to identify enemy cells to the immune system, ovarian cancer was observed to disappear for more than 18 months.
The method is to extract the immune cells from the patient, change them in the laboratory so that they can “watch” a protein common to many cancers called HER2, and then inject those cells again to the patient.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results indicate that this vaccine is very well-suited.”
HER2 “drives the growth of several types of cancers,” including breast, ovarian, lung and colon cancer, explained Prof. Berzofsky.
A similar approach to taking immune cells from patients and “learning” their localization of cancer cells worked in the treatment of a certain type of leukemia.
