Previous articleHIV/AIDS: China Reports 14 Percent Increase in New Cases
China has announced a 14 percent increase in the number of people living with HIV and suffering from AIDS.
More than 820,000 people are affected by this problem, according to the country’s health services.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, about 40,000 new cases were reported.
The vast majority of new cases have been transmitted by gender, which means a change from the past.
Traditionally, the HIV virus spreads rapidly in some parts of China as a result of transfusion of infected blood.
However, the number of people infected with HIV in this way has been reduced almost entirely, according to Chinese health officials at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, year on year, the number of people living with HIV and suffering from AIDS in China has increased by 100,000.
Sexual transmission of HIV is a serious problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is widespread.
Taking into account the country’s conservative values, studies estimate that 70-90% of men who have sex with men will eventually marry a woman.
Many cases of transmission of the disease result from insufficient protection when having sex in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has provided widespread access to HIV drugs as part of efforts to combat this problem.
