The creator of the World Wide Web is planning to launch a new Internet in order to compete with Google and Facebook platforms.
Tim Berners-Lee, creator of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google platforms.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company based on an open source platform — Solid — belonging to Berners-Lee.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and which individuals have access to specific information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the goal of creating Inrupt was “dominance over the world.”
“We have to do it now,” he said, referring to the start-up.
“The historic moment has come.”
The application uses Solid platform technology to allow people to create their own “personal data online store” or otherwise POD.
It can include contact lists, lists of things to do, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify available in one browser and at the same time.
The unique feature of an online store with personal data is that it is entirely up to the user who has access to what information.
The company calls this “personal empowerment through data.”
